    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="entry" xml:id="main_text">
                <head>Persepolis</head>
                <p>
                    <placeName ref="#persepolis">Persepolis</placeName> was the ceremonial capital of the
                    <orgName ref="#achaemenid">Achaemenid Empire</orgName>, founded by
                    <persName ref="#cyrus">Cyrus the Great</persName> and built as a monumental
                    complex by <persName ref="#darius">Darius the Great</persName> beginning in
                    518 BCE, in what is today <placeName ref="#fars">Fars Province</placeName>, near
                    the modern city of <placeName ref="#marvdasht">Marvdasht</placeName>. Before
                    Darius chose this site, the Achaemenid kings ruled from
                    <placeName ref="#pasargadae">Pasargadae</placeName>, the empire's first capital,
                    which Cyrus had built roughly forty kilometres to the northeast. Darius
                    commissioned the site's grandest buildings, including the
                    <name ref="#tachara">Tachara</name>, his private palace, and began the
                    <name ref="#apadana">Apadana</name>, the great audience hall, which his son and
                    successor <persName ref="#xerxes">Xerxes I</persName> completed and further
                    expanded with the construction of the
                    <name ref="#gate_of_all_nations">Gate of All Nations</name>. The kings whose
                    likenesses appear throughout the site practiced
                    <name ref="#zoroastrianism">Zoroastrianism</name>, and the trilingual royal
                    inscriptions carved into its walls, written partly in
                    <name ref="#old_persian">Old Persian</name>, represent some of the earliest
                    deciphered examples of that language. Nearby, at
                    <placeName ref="#naqshe_rustam">Naqsh-e Rustam</placeName>, the tombs of Darius
                    and Xerxes were cut into a cliff face overlooking the plain. In 330 BCE,
                    <persName ref="#alexander">Alexander the Great</persName> captured and burned
                    Persepolis during his conquest of the Achaemenid Empire, effectively ending
                    organized Persian resistance in the region. The ruins lay largely unexcavated
                    until the twentieth century, when the German archaeologist
                    <persName ref="#herzfeld">Ernst Herzfeld</persName> began systematic
                    excavations in 1931 on behalf of the
                    <orgName ref="#isac">Institute for the Study of Ancient Cultures</orgName> at
                    the University of Chicago; Herzfeld's team uncovered the
                    <name ref="#fortification_archive">Persepolis Administrative Archives</name>, a
                    collection of clay tablets documenting the empire's daily administration.
                    Herzfeld was succeeded as expedition director by
                    <persName ref="#schmidt">Erich Schmidt</persName> in 1934, who continued the
                    excavations until 1939. In recognition of its outstanding cultural value,
                    <orgName ref="#unesco">UNESCO</orgName> inscribed Persepolis on the World
                    Heritage List in 1979
                    <ref target="#wiki_persepolis_ref" type="citation">(Wikipedia contributors)</ref>.
                </p>
            </div>
        </body>
